if iam user does not have those actions ?

Access Denied — the call fails immediately at the API level, before it even reaches the resource.

User/Role tries: kms:Decrypt
IAM checks: Does policy have "kms:Decrypt" listed?
   ❌ NO → AccessDeniedException — request rejected
   ✅ YES → proceed to check KMS Key Policy too

You can do it at either level — bucket-level (recommended) or object-level (per-request). Let me break down both:

1. Bucket-level (Default Encryption) — set once, applies to everything

S3 Console → Bucket → Properties → Default encryption
   → Enable
   → Encryption type: SSE-KMS
   → Choose KMS key (your CMK or aws/s3 managed key)

Good question — clarify: AWS auto-provides a DEFAULT key, but a CMK you must always create yourself. Never auto-created.

Both options exist — you choose one:

Option 1: aws/s3 (AWS managed key) — already exists, zero setup

• AWS creates this automatically in every account
• No need to create anything — just select it from the dropdown
• Free-ish (no monthly key fee, only API call charges)
• You don't control rotation, policy, or cross-account sharing

Option 2: Customer Managed Key (CMK) — you must create it yourself

• Goes to KMS console → Create Key → Symmetric → give it an alias (e.g., alias/my-app-s3-key)
• You control: key policy, rotation schedule, cross-account access, ability to disable/delete it
• Costs ~$1/month per key + API charges
• Needed when you want fine-grained access control (e.g., only certain roles can decrypt, not the whole account)

